##In the midst of the outbreak, we have 80 cameras in Shanghai, monitoring the city's wildlife

Weixin Guokr42

Functional introductions, science and technology, are the language we speak to the world.

The following article was written by Wang Fang, a nature surveyor

Nature Surveyor Florida measures the forest, touches the wind and rain, photographs animals, and tells a story full of holes

At the moment, wildlife is a touchy subject -- on one hand, the inability to eat or catch wild animals is slowly becoming accepted, and on the other hand, the virus is triggering a fear of bats, along with the city's occasional hedgehogs, weasels and raccoons.

What can Wildlife Research and conservation teams do now?

In fact, our work has never been more urgent. This urgency not only comes from the wilderness, but also spreads to the city ———————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————————— So that we can make a reasonable management plan. Where do biodiversity management, Risk Assessment and disease control begin when no one can say for sure where city-by-city hedgehogs, weasels and bats are located? Well, you can't guess with your head.

Whether it's species conservation or natural resource management, it's important to understand. Without understanding, everything loses its foundation.

BIODIVERSITY: neglected
The issue of complexity

We have been erasing the nature of the city bit by bit, and now we are making amends bit by bit. In the past few years, urban biodiversity has been routinely considered the best thing that ever happened to it by ecologists because of past mistakes.

However, one of the key issues on the complex topic of biodiversity may be overlooked -- biodiversity is biodiversity. In a sense, the word "diversity" is the essence of the world. It does not mean absolute beauty, nor does it mean evil.

A resident helps a Mallard duck escape after it fell into a swimming pool in Beijing

In Virginia in the United States, I've been fascinated by the biodiversity represented by raccoons and skunks. It started when a large-headed raccoon pulled open my sliding door and stared up at the watery eyes for food. Knocking and bowing from door to door, he got a steady stream of cat food and water.

Over the next few days, the raccoon terrorized our entire research facility, as if it had climbed a telephone pole, followed a power line into an office, ransacked several rooms of garbage cans, and trashed food in the refrigerator. Then it caused a short in the power lines, a blackout at the ECOLAB and the geo-analysis lab, and the raccoon itself was killed in the accident.

I later learned that almost every single citizen in the United States can tell stories of being harassed by wildlife, not only in the form of house destruction, but also in the form of fires, pollution, infectious diseases, and ten million dollars a year in property damage..

The raccoon crowding into the room brings disaster to the institute | Wang Dajun

Nowadays, people pay more attention to and protect the urban nature. As a research team, we are concerned about the complex changes in biodiversity that will occur as cities become more ecologically sound.

In Berlin, for example, 3,000 wild boars, which make their home in the city, regularly disturb parks and neighborhoods. In London and Bristol, more than 18 red foxes per square kilometre have revolutionised the composition of terrestrial mammals and birds, and thus soil, water, and even agriculture and animal husbandry.

The NFW.ORG  

The rapid adaptation of animals to urban life is in fact accompanied by deeper biological changes -- extraordinary adaptations that enable certain groups of animals to pillage cities and occupy settlements, to invade human life in this way.

This is the dark side of the moon for biodiversity, and one of the most spectacular changes on earth.

So, what to do?

To put it simply: The conservation and management of urban biodiversity is a challenging, ever-changing, never-ending Journey.

To complicate things a bit: Diversity is the nature of the world, whether you like it or not.

Unlike the wild, cities can not give animals a paradise of undisturbed habitat. They can only live with people. And time and time again, the lessons prove, poisoning, culling these easy to remember in the first time measures, have no way to control the adaptability of animals, but will cause a chain of ecological disaster, bringing more difficult to deal with the consequences.

Even when artificial means are needed to control a resilient urban species, brute force methods are often ineffective

Premise of management: collection
Information on the distribution and habits of animals

In Qingpu District, Shanghai, I had some wonderful times with a raccoon dog. He might have thought I was a good companion, sitting at my feet several times, crunching and tickling in the middle of the night.

Raccoon dog is a kind of interesting existence. On the one hand, everyone has heard of the idiom "birds of a feather" . On the other hand, people don't even know that it is a real animal, but just regard it as a legendary monster.

The legendary raccoon dog, widely distributed in Shanghai | Wang Fang

When we began to systematically track urban raccoon dogs, we found that this mythical species was found in large numbers in cities around the Yangtze River Delta, from Shanghai to Nanjing, from Suzhou to Hangzhou, they can be seen all over the Yangtze River Delta. Professor Xu Zhengqiang of the Shanghai Zoo and his team have recorded racoon dog in more than 40 neighborhoods in downtown Shanghai alone.

And as we continue to watch, we discover the species'urban metamorphosis -- the ability to dive into a river near a community in Qingpu District, Florida, to become a superb swimmer In Jinshan District, the Raccoon Dog Habitat is surrounded by hilly thickets that demonstrate amazing skills in digging, jumping, and frog hunting. In Fengxian District and Nanhui, they quickly understand campus and community design, between the cracks of the human world.

Such adaptability is a reminder that the land is home to species as diverse as the berliner boar and the London Red Fox. As China's urban environment continues to improve, Callosciurus Erythraeus and chipmunks, racoon dogs and badgers, hedgehogs and wild pigs may one day pose complex urban management problems.

A simple corollary is that if we don't understand the distribution and numbers of these species, and don't monitor their population growth and decline, and their adaptations, then the day that there's really any problem, isn't the only way to manage urban biodiversity is to tap your head?

Urban Biodiversity:
Everyone's opinion counts

The story comes back to raccoon. In Shanghai and Nanjing, raccoons have found an easier and more accessible source of food by eating human waste. Their hiding environment has changed from caves and roots to cracks under balconies, voids in walls, storerooms, cracks in piers, gas pipes, abandoned sewers and so on.

But when we ran into the neighborhood, things didn't turn out the way we thought they would. Some of the townsfolk thought it was funny, but some of the community came up and said, "can we kill them? " And "This badger is a pain in the ASS! "

I asked an aunt why she was so negative about cats, and she answered simply and persuasively -- like cats that feed on cats, but she found that NYCTS may prey on newborn kittens.

I tried to tell her that racoon dogs were the natives of the land, and that stray cats were the latecomers after the land had been occupied by the inhabitants, and that the chief culprit was their abandonment. But whatever the ecological process behind it, we understand the aunt's appeal, and we understand that she had reason to be upset about raccoon dog killing her favorite cat cub.

The same story goes on: When residents ask us if raccoon dogs can transmit rabies, we say it's theoretically possible, not only for rabies, but also for sarcoptes Mites, distemper, parvovirus, and so on. Although these diseases are transmitted from stray cats and dogs to raccoon dogs, in any case, there is a risk in the city.

When people ask us if a Hedgehog is at risk, we say it depends on whether it's an encephalitis area, whether there's an epidemic, but yes, hedgehogs may carry bloodsucking ticks, but as long as you don't touch them, you're fine...

A simple hedgehog may have dozens of bloodsucking ticks on it

It's our job to investigate animals. We've designed surveillance networks in cities, using occupational models, Bayesian methods, and so on.

How to manage the urban ecosystem, I am afraid, needs to integrate everyone's opinion.

What do we do? Since everyone's opinion matters in the management of biodiversity in cities, why not involve everyone?

Before the outbreak, we organized a citizen team to begin a citizen science expedition.

80 Cameras, 100 people:
A city of animals

At the moment, in Shanghai, there are 80 infrared triggered cameras recording the distribution and changes of urban animals day and night, whether it is the peak of the garden around the National Day and the New Year's Day, or the desolation of the holidays, or perhaps it's the closing of the garden under the shadow of the epidemic.

A team of citizen scientists surveys the city's animals in Gucun Park January 2,2020 | Wu Yigan

We began a full survey of wildlife in cities, their behavior, their relationship to humans, and their adaptation to environmental change, successfully activating our surveillance network before the outbreak began.

The survey took place in Gongqing Forest Park, Ben Giang Forest Park, Shanghai Botanical Garden, Shanghai Zoo, Minhang District Sports Park, Hongxu community, Fudan University campus, Shanghai Ocean University campus, Nanhui suburbs, Pujiang County (Zhejiang) country park and Gucun Park.

At the moment you read this, the network is recording all the time with no one watching.

We have recorded the distribution and habits of more than 40 species of animals

In addition to the Fudan University, a team of citizen scientists, nearly 100 citizens, completed the survey.

These contactless investigations minimise the risk to the public of direct contact with animals. At the same time, each "citizen scientist" has his or her own wishes and interests, and will input his or her own expectations for a better urban ecology in the project.

We're producing two things:

Continuous survey of Urban Animals;
Public opinion that continues to grow.

Taken together, these two outputs may have the opportunity to provide an answer to what we know, expect, and demand for urban biodiversity today.

The new pneumonia raises the great question of whether the animals in the wild can coexist? How do we coexist? The cities of our country are desperate for an answer.

And these 80 cameras and 100 people want to do two things:

Accumulation of basic data, as the basis of all management programs;
Combining the power of citizens and integrating public opinion.

These tasks have never been more urgent. Behind this whole job is our hope for a better world.

By Wang Fang
Editor: You Shiyou
